[1] Liberia: further investigation of new case
Date: Thu 26 Nov 2015
Source: Foreign Policy [edited]
http://foreignpolicy.com/2015/11/26/how-liberias-latest-ebola-case-slipped-through-the-cracks/


Just weeks after Liberia was declared Ebola free, the newest case of Ebola virus disease (EVD) revealed worrying problems with remaining EVD-free.

Looking for treatment, the index patient of this latest chain of transmission "traveled in a car from a crowded clinic with his father and 4 other people. He was weak and bleeding from the mouth. Finally, [the patient] was seen at John F. Kennedy Medical Center in Monrovia, Liberia's capital. The JFK facility is the largest public hospital in Liberia. Upon entry to the facility, his father claimed he had been cut during an accident. He did not have a fever. None of the health-care triage workers suspected EVD. He was unable to walk. His father pushed him in a wheelchair to the trauma ward, where a nurse in every-day scrubs and latex gloves examined the inside of his bleeding mouth. Finding no source of bleeding, she sent him to the children's emergency ward. It was 2 days later when he tested positive for EVD. He was immediately sent to an Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU). He died 3 days later.

There are several steps where his treatment failed both [the patient] and West Africa, contributing to his death and the creation of a new chain of transmission:
- While obviously very ill, he traveled by car with 4 other people to a crowded clinic and JFK Medical Center, increasing the chance of EVD transmission to the vehicle's occupants and the medical care facilities he visited.
- Once in the facility, his father inaccurately described the source of the bleeding as being due to being cut during an accident. According to Dr. Mosoka Fallah, "There should be a high level of suspicion because 90 percent of the patients lie."
- The medical staff who worked on him did not wear appropriate equipment for evaluating and treating a patient with EVD.
- According to Dr. Fallah, the leader of the outbreak response who traced most of the cases through Monrovia and Liberia during the height of the outbreak, his treating staff at medical facilities relied too much on his lack of fever as an indication of possible EVD infection.

On the other hand, Dr. Francis Kateh, the chief medical officer and acting head of the Incidence Management System that manages Ebola cases, denied there had been a breach of protocol. "No one would walk around with full [personal protective equipment] in this climate."

According to Dr. Kateh, 9 health-care-worker contacts are quarantined, and 152 contacts have been identified. Of the 152 contacts, 18 are avoiding the contact tracers.

The children's emergency ward at the hospital has been decontaminated and is closed. The patients have been discharged home to observation. The nurse who examined NG in the trauma is quarantined, but that ward has not been decontaminated. His 8-year-old brother and his father contracted EVD, but remain in stable condition, as do his mother and 2 younger siblings. All are receiving Zmapp. His family home has been decontaminated.

What is so troublesome about the case is that what should have been obvious warning signs were not investigated for critical days.

On Mon 23 Nov 2015, scientists from the United States Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (USAMRIID) arrived in Liberia to do genetic sequencing tests to determine whether the new infections are linked to a previous chain of transmission. Concerns remain about basic infection prevention and control in health clinics and hospitals in Liberia.

According to Aitor Sanchez-Lacomba, the director of the International Rescue Committee in Liberia "While 'post-Ebola' planning has focused on long-term aspirations, the very gaps in basic infection control that facilitated the epidemic's growth in the 1st place have still not been addressed. These include having water, sanitation, and basic equipment at facilities; ongoing community surveillance; and triage procedures adapted not only for Ebola, but other epidemic diseases."

Liberia's 2 small outbreaks bring into question concerns about the World Health Organization (WHO)'s "Ebola-free" classification after 42 days without a case.

Dr. Fallah said NG's mother "may have been a survivor," something investigators are following as a possible explanation for the latest outbreak.

A recent report by the Environmental Foundation for Africa investigated how potential threats of virus diseases, like EVD, will grow as humans continue to encroach on local wildlife. A comprehensive study into this issue will soon begin.

